            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Scott Kowalski is a product of San Francisco's fog-laced Outer Sunset, born and raised in a small house his carpenter father and part-time bookkeeper mother bought in the 1970s. Growing up, his world was Ocean Beach bonfires, Giants games on a crackly radio, and the hum of his father\u2019s tools in the garage. Scott was never one for academics; he found classrooms suffocating and graduated from Abraham Lincoln High School with a C-average and no real plan.\n\nFor a decade, he drifted through jobs that paid the bills but offered little future: changing tires at a garage in Daly City, stocking shelves at a grocery warehouse, and driving for a courier service. The city was changing around him, with tech money flooding in, and Scott felt increasingly left behind. The turning point came at 28, when a friend\u2019s father, a retiring Muni operator, urged him to apply. The stability, the union, the pension\u2014it was a lifeline. He got the job.\n\nFor the past sixteen years, Scott has been behind the wheel of a city bus. His route is a rolling diorama of the city's soul, from the weary faces on the early morning 38-Geary to the cheerful tourists on the F-Market streetcar. He\u2019s a quiet observer, a keeper of the city\u2019s transient stories. A short-lived marriage in his early thirties ended amicably, leaving him with his currently quiet two-bedroom house in the Excelsior. His social circle is small but tight\u2014a few other drivers he shoots pool with at a dive bar and his sister in Sacramento, whom he calls every Sunday.\n\nHis life is a testament to routine. He drives his 2012 Honda Accord the 6.8 miles to the bus yard before dawn, returning home in the afternoon to the familiar comfort of his worn armchair and a baseball game on TV. His connection to San Francisco is a complicated mix of native pride and quiet resentment for the city it has become. His dream isn't of wealth, but of peace: to pay off his mortgage, retire in his early sixties, and maybe buy a small fishing boat to take out on the Delta\u2014a simple, quiet life after a career spent navigating the noisy heart of his ever-changing hometown."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was maybe ten when his dad let him hold the chalk line in the garage. The air was thick with the smell of sawdust and old coffee. His father, a man of few words, stretched the line tight across a plank of Douglas fir, pulled it back, and let it snap. A perfect, sharp blue line appeared. \"Measure twice, cut once,\" his dad grunted, not as a lesson, but as a law of the universe. In that moment, Scott understood the deep satisfaction of getting something exactly right, a feeling of order he would later find in a perfectly timed bus route.\n\n***\n\n2.\nAt 26, working as a courier, he delivered a sleek architect's model to a new high-rise in SoMa. He stood in the gleaming lobby, feeling grubby in his work jacket as young men in expensive sweaters glided past, talking about equity and burn rates. Looking out at the cranes remaking the skyline, a cold wave of invisibility washed over him. This wasn't his San Francisco anymore; he was just a ghost servicing its new, wealthier inhabitants. That quiet resentment took root then, a feeling of being a stranger in his own home.\n\n***\n\n3.\nHis first solo morning run on the 38-Geary, gripping the huge steering wheel in the pre-dawn dark. Pulling up to a stop, the doors hissed open and the first passengers boarded: a cook, a nurse, an office cleaner, their faces tired but etched with purpose. He wasn't just driving a machine; he was carrying the city\u2019s lifeblood. In their silent, weary nods, he felt a profound sense of responsibility and connection. For the first time in a decade, he felt essential. He had a place again.\n\n***\n\n4.\nHe and his wife were painting the living room of their new Excelsior house. She was excitedly talking about a trip to Italy, about seeing art, about a life bigger than their two bedrooms. He looked at the perfect, straight line he\u2019d just cut with the paint roller along the ceiling, and realized the quiet satisfaction of that single task was more real to him than any far-flung dream. There wasn't a fight, just the sad, silent understanding that they wanted different things from the world. Their peace was found on opposite sides of a map.\n\n***\n\n5.\nJust last year, an elderly woman\u2019s grocery bag split open on his bus, spilling oranges down the aisle. Before he could say a word, a tech kid with headphones and a punk girl with green hair were on their knees, silently gathering the fruit. They handed the bag back to the woman, shared a quick, anonymous nod, and got off at the next stop. Scott watched them go in his mirror, feeling a familiar ache in his chest\u2014a flicker of hope for the city\u2019s soul, a reminder of the quiet decency that still rattled along its streets."
